title: Grateful Dead Live at Beacon Theatre on 1976-06-14
description:
Set 1

Cold Rain & Snow, Mama Tried, Row Jimmy, Cassidy, Brown Eyed Women, Big River, Might As Well, Lazy Lightning-> Supplication, Tennessee Jed, Playin' In The Band

Set 2

The Wheel, Samson & Delilah, High Time, The Music Never Stopped, Crazy Fingers-> Dancin' In The Streets-> Cosmic Charlie-> Help On The Way-> Slipknot!-> Franklin's Tower-> Around & Around, E: U.S. Blues

reviews.review_text:
Slipknot era 1976 is for me the peak era for slipknots. Great jazzy show all over, and the usual quality from Scott, Charlie, Tim, and Betty.

Thank you all for not letting the Dead fade away even as 2019 approaches.
Beacon 6-14-76' This is top shelf 76' Dead.The second set is excellently performed with an amazing Cosmic Charlie and jazzy H>S>F to end the show.
Don’t Sleep on This! Audio quality is fantastic on this show. This show as many others from the period shine. Thank you for the transfer! My favorite version of this show available on the archive.

Best ever Slipknot! Love this show. June '76 is hot as it is, but this might be the creme de la creme. So many great renditions of Dead classics at this show. PitB has a bit of '74-esque playing in it, and obviously the H>S>F might get the most attention but the Slipknot! by itself is THE version of this song IMO.

Other highlights include: Brown Eyed Women, Cassidy, Lazy Lighting>Supplication, the whole CRAZY FINGERS (another definitive version IMO)>Dancin'>Cosmic Charlie that precedes the H>S>F. The Dead were ON in the mid-'70s! '76-77 is a legendary peak in the band's history, but these Summer '76 shows are something special. And this recording is so crystal clear. Turn your bass up because you're gonna wanna pay extra attention to Phil on this night. No Phil Bombs (that I'm aware of anyway), but if you want a masterclass in effortless "walking" bass runs, this show is 3.5 hours worth of that.

Thank you to Betty & Tim for providing the tapes! Wave that flag.
